Reference-contexts: From his field observations, Gasser concludes it is anything but routine. It is quite wrong to regard routine work as the slavish following of bureaucratic rules and procedures. Much of so-called routine work is skilled problem-solving <ref> (see also Wynn, 1979) </ref>. Offices are open systems; anomaly is ubiquitous; often the correct procedure is not mechanically obvious, indeed often procedures must be adapted to suit the exigencies of the situation. For these reasons, no formal description can ever completely cover the contingent, ever-varying character of real work.
